<DOC><DOCNO> AP890731-0224 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0943EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Japan-TaxEvasion     07-31 0151</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Japan-Tax Evasion,0156</SECOND><HEAD>Record Amount of Taxes Evaded in Fiscal 1987</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Japanese government reported Monday that arecord $5.17 billion in income was not reported by independentbusiness owners in fiscal 1987.   The National Tax Administration Agency said it investigated168,926 people nationwide, including doctors, lawyers and otherindependent business owners, and discovered that 95.8 percent ofthem reported their incomes incorrectly, either by mistake or fortax evasion.   The undeclared earnings discovered by the agency were 13.7percent larger than in fiscal 1986, the agency said. Fiscal 1987ended on March 31, 1988.   The agency said it levied a record $1.36 billion in penaltyfines, up 18.4 percent from 1986.   Owners of pinball parlors topped the 1987 list of tax evaderswith an average $270,000 in unreported income, followed by hospitalowners, with an average $115,000 and real estate businesses with$93,000, the agency said.</TEXT></DOC>